    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1893-03-25T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1893-03-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="263" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d263">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Tsui Kwo Yin</persName> to
                                Mr. <persName type="to">Gresham</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chinese
                                        Legation</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington, D.
                                    C.</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1893-03-25">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 25, 1893</hi>
                        </date>.
                                (Received March 27.)</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the
                            receipt of your note of the 21st instant, in which you advise me that
                            the request presented in my note of the 13th instant has been considered
                            by the Attorney-General of the United States, and that he will be glad
                            to concur in the motion to advance a test case in the Supreme Court
                            involving the constitutionality of the Chinese prohibition and exclusion
                            law, known as the “Geary act,” and that he will also do all in his power
                            to secure the advancement of the case and its early determination.</p>
                <p>The willingness of the Attorney-General to cooperate with counsel
                            representing the Chinese in such a case will be communicated to Mr.
                            Heber J. May, Washington, D. C., counsel to this legation, and through
                            him to the counsel individually representing my people in the United
                            States.</p>
                <p>Accept, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Tsui Kwo Yin</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
